		<td width="18"><img src="/Graphics/Interface/Icons/spacer.gif" width=18 height=1 border=0></td>
	
	
		<td>
	




	<font size="-1"><b>CES -- Where Entertainment, Content and Technology Converge</b></font>

	<p>Arlington, VA - Sep, 27 1999
	<BR>
	Entertainment, computer, communications and consumer technology will converge at Digital Hollywood at the 2000 International CES -Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology, in Las Vegas, January 6-9, 2000.  From demonstrations of Internet MP3 audio downloads and video streaming, to keynote addresses and conference sessions by visionaries from the entertainment, content and technology industries, the entertainment marketplace of the future will be on display at Digital Hollywood. <P>
"One of the most exciting aspects of the digital revolution is the amazing innovation that Hollywood and the entertainment industry is driving via consumer technologies," said Robbi Lycett, CES vice president.  "With MP3 and the continuing convergence of digital video, TVs and PCs, it is little wonder that entertainment continues to evolve.  The cutting edge of entertainment is happening at Digital Hollywood, reshaping and reconstructing modern concepts of audio, video and multimedia and how those media are distributed."  <P>
Conference Sessions <P>
Addressing the convergence of entertainment and technology, Digital Hollywood conference sessions will focus on digital media and content production and are geared toward computer and Internet companies; telephone companies; broadcast, cable and satellite executives; and entertainment and studio executives.  Some of this year's sessions include: <P>
* The TV and PC Internet Connection: Technology, Commerce and Content * Digital Music: From the Internet into the Home * Cable, Telcos and Satellite as Broadband Entertainment Providers * The Internet Networks Go Broadband: Entertainment, Services and Commerce * Digital Entertainment Convergence: A Content and Technology Explosion of TV, Music, Cable and the Internet * Views on the Digital Home: The TV Hub, Computer Hub and Telecommunications Hub * Technology Infrastructure for the Delivery of Broadband Entertainment * Update on Digital Piracy and Copyright Infringement * The Free Home Computer: Internet Phenomenon * Development of Streaming Video Programming: The Launch of an Internet Entertainment Channel * The Music Industry: Narrowband and Broadband Strategies * Investment and Venture Capital in Broadband: From Incubator of Ideas and Talent to Financier of Operations * Entertainment and Information Content: Leveraging and Merging the TV and Internet Medias  * Interactive TV/DTV Software and Programming Solutions * Digital TV Cable/Satellite Box: New Services,  New Revenue * Downloading Music on the Internet: MP3, MS Audio, A2B and Other Killer Technologies * Digital Storytelling @ Digital Hollywood * E-Commerce for Media Companies and Their Enterprise Partners * Implications of Emerging DTV, Internet, HDTV and Broadband Technologies * Selling Entertainment as well as Consumer Electronics on the Web * Strategies for Broadband-Narrowband Entertainment * Consumers Interact with Computing/TV Devices: The Future of Commerce * Personalized E-Commerce Sites for the Consumer * Internet Advertising Strategies: Implementing National vs. Local Programs * Developing Online Promotions: Traffic and Brand * Building Compelling 3D Communities and E-Commerce Venues on the Internet * E-Commerce is about Partnerships: Structuring your Web Relationships * DVD, Home Video and other Entertainment Technologies and Devices * The Household, Internet or Mobile Appliance: The Personal Taskmasters  	 "Digital Hollywood will examine the reality of digital convergence," Lycett said.   "This is where the TV, the Internet, content and commerce all meet."  He added that the conferences would address business, content, technology and legal issues.  <P>
Exhibit Areas <P>
To help attendees navigate the show floor and get the most out of each day, CES is divided into product category sections and technology pavilions.  For the 2000 show, Digital Hollywood exhibits will be located in the North Hall of the Las Vegas Convention Center (LVCC).   There, Digital Hollywood exhibitors will enjoy access to more than 90,000 attendees, including more than 80,000 buyers of home theater, audio/visual and/or satellite products. <P>
A wide variety of companies representing all facets of digital entertainment will be exhibiting products at the 2000 International CES.  For example, MCY.com and Hollywood Stock Exchange will demonstrate MP3-type technology with extra security features to address copy protection concerns.  Yamaha will show its PC audio receiver, while Sony, CMI Worldwide and many others will exhibit new digital entertainment products.  Other registered exhibitors include: 3Com, America Online, Cisco, Compact Flash, Creative Labs, Diamond Multimedia, Microsoft, Pinnacle Systems, RealNetworks, Replay Networks, Sandisk, Sensory Science, Sun Microsystems and TiVo. <P>
CES, as the premier showcase of lifestyle and workstyle technologies, also will feature four industry-leading pioneers as keynoters.  Eric A. Benhamou, chairman and CEO, 3Com Corp.; Scott McNealy, chairman and CEO, Sun Microsystems; Rob Glaser, chairman and CEO, RealNetworks Inc.; and Bill Gates, chairman and CEO, Microsoft Corp., will deliver the Opening Keynote, the Executive Perspective Keynote, the Technology Keynote and the New Millennium Keynote addresses, respectively.  <P>
